Subject:Re: [EVDL] Old and new in pack
Can I use my high current charger until about 80 percent charged and then
switch to individual chargers for the last 20 percent and avoid
overcharging and undercharging?

Kiff
 On Oct 16, 2012 1:25 PM, "Lee Hart" <leeahart@earthlink.net> wrote:

> On 10/16/2012 11:30 AM, Kiff Wilson wrote:
> > I have been surprised to see my oldest batteries are gassing/bubbling and
> > not my new ones.  I had previously thought that the newest batteries get
> > overcharged but apparently not with my marine batteries.  I am using an
> > elcon pfc-2500 charging the batteries as a pack and not individually.  I
> > used a stethoscope to listen to the batteries.
>
> Most flooded batteries use lead alloyed with trace amounts of antimony.
> The antimony strengthens the lead, but also increases gassing.
>
> As the battery ages, the constant plating and deplating of the lead
> allows the antimony to migrate to the surface. The higher antimony
> concentration makes the cell gas more, and start gassing at a lower
> voltage. If you charge a new and an old battery in series, the old one
> will start gassing sooner, will gas more, and consequently use more water.
>
> The gassing reaction takes current away from the charging reaction.
> Suppose your battery needs 2 amps of finishing current to reach "full"
> when new. When it gets old, the same 2 amps just makes it keep gassing
> forever, and it never does reach "full". So you have to charge it at a
> higher finishing current, like 3 amps. 1 amp is used up by the gassing,
> and the other 2 amps actually finishes charging it.
>
> The old battery never will come up to quite as high a voltage as the new
> battery, even when fully charged. 2 amps would get a new battery up to
> 15v; but 3 or even 4 amps might only get the old one up to 14.6v.
>
> Now you can see the problem with charging new and old batteries in
> series. The charger only knows the total voltage, and doesn't change its
> finishing current to allow for old batteries. So, it will tend to supply
> too little finishing current, and charge too long in an attempt to get
> the total voltage up to 15v per 12v battery (like 14.5v on the old one,
> and 15.5v on the new one). This undercharges the old battery (not enough
> current) and overcharges the new battery (too much voltage for too long).
>
> To make it work, you need to a) increase the finishing current so the
> old battery is happy, and b) bypass some of the charging current around
> the new battery to slow or stop its charging rate so it won't get
> overcharged.
> --
